post_cb({"3931202": {"ParentId": "3931167", "CommentCount": "1", "Body": "<p>Those for bytes are the reference. A reference is just a pointer internally, and pointers typically use 4 bytes on a 32bit system, irrespective of the data types because it is just an address, not the value itself.</p>\n", "OwnerUserId": "429435", "PostTypeId": "2", "Id": "3931202", "Score": "7", "CreationDate": "2010-10-14T08:02:26.197", "LastActivityDate": "2010-10-14T08:02:26.197"}, "3931167": {"CommentCount": "0", "CreationDate": "2010-10-14T07:58:50.350", "PostTypeId": "1", "AcceptedAnswerId": "3931202", "LastEditorUserId": "1288", "LastActivityDate": "2012-09-21T17:13:29.397", "LastEditDate": "2012-09-21T17:13:29.397", "ViewCount": "653", "FavoriteCount": "2", "Title": "Why reference variable inside class always taking 4 bytes irrespect of type? (on 32-bit system)", "Id": "3931167", "Score": "6", "Body": "<p>I have below code, running on 32-bit windows, visual-studio.</p>\n<pre><code>template &lt;class T&gt;\nclass Test\n{\npublic:\n T &amp;ref;\n Test(T &amp;x)\n  :ref(x)\n {}\n};\n\nint main()\n{\n cout&lt;&lt;\"sizeof Test&lt;int&gt; : \"&lt;&lt;sizeof(Test&lt;int&gt;)&lt;&lt;endl;\n cout&lt;&lt;\"sizeof Test&lt;double&gt; : \"&lt;&lt;sizeof(Test&lt;double&gt;)&lt;&lt;endl;\n cout&lt;&lt;\"sizeof Test&lt;char&gt; : \"&lt;&lt;sizeof(Test&lt;char&gt;)&lt;&lt;endl;\n}\n</code></pre>\n<p>Output is:</p>\n<pre><code>sizeof Test&lt;int&gt; : 4\nsizeof Test&lt;double&gt; : 4\nsizeof Test&lt;char&gt; : 4\n</code></pre>\n<p>Compiler giving 4 bytes for reference variable inside class irrespect of the type of reference. Variable value can not be stored in those 4 bytes.</p>\n<p>What information compiler will store in those 4 bytes ?</p>\n<p>is it internally storing the address of referent? so that reference and referent both can write to the same location to be in sync with each other.</p>\n<p>Or is it storing name of referent in symbol table ?</p>\n", "Tags": "<c++><visual-studio-2008>", "OwnerUserId": "426051", "AnswerCount": "2"}, "3931551": {"ParentId": "3931167", "CommentCount": "9", "Body": "<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_3931167_3931551_0\">Why reference variable inside class always taking 4 bytes irrespect of type?</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p><a href=\"http://ideone.com/qdqO2\" rel=\"nofollow\">It isn't!</a></p>\n<p>C++03 <code>5.3.3</code></p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_3931167_3931551_1\">When applied to a reference or a reference type, the result is the <strong>size of the referenced type</strong>.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Also <code>8.3.2</code> says</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_3931167_3931551_2\">It is <strong>unspecified</strong> whether or not a reference requires storage.</p>\n</blockquote>\n", "OwnerUserId": "165520", "PostTypeId": "2", "Id": "3931551", "Score": "0", "CreationDate": "2010-10-14T08:52:47.970", "LastActivityDate": "2010-10-14T08:52:47.970"}, "bq_ids": {"n4140": {"so_3931167_3931551_2": {"section_id": 3221, "quality": 1.0, "length": 5}, "so_3931167_3931551_1": {"section_id": 6077, "quality": 1.0, "length": 9}}, "n3337": {"so_3931167_3931551_2": {"section_id": 3095, "quality": 1.0, "length": 5}, "so_3931167_3931551_1": {"section_id": 5845, "quality": 1.0, "length": 9}}, "n4659": {"so_3931167_3931551_2": {"section_id": 3978, "quality": 1.0, "length": 5}, "so_3931167_3931551_1": {"section_id": 7573, "quality": 1.0, "length": 9}}}});